definition.value: A group marriage which is registered as a legal corporation to circumnavigate such marriages not being recognized in many areas.
A marriage with a legal clause which disallows divorce or simple divorce.
Engaging in romantic activities only with one's parter or partners.
A fear of being abandoned or neglected by a sexual partner, especially if that partner expresses romantic and/or sexual interest in another person or persons.
A four-person group marriage, usually with two men and two women.
Swinging in which additional partners are not anonymous or random, but persons who are already close friends.
A friend with whom one participates in sexual activities with.
Non-monogamous relationships or arrangements in which partners are permitted to pursue other persons sexually when physically apart.
A relationship in which the persons involved do not live together and are separated by some distance in which seeing each other regularly is uncommon.
A relationship in which the persons involved do not live together, but are not separated by distance and so see each other regularly.
A partner in a polyamorous relationship who is noted as having a higher degree of emotional and/or sexual involvement than a non-primary partner.

A family group consisting of two parents and their children (one or more). It is in contrast to a single-parent family, the larger extended family, and a family with more than two parents. Nuclear families typically center on a married couple; the nuclear family may have any number of children.
A partner in a polyamorous relationship who is noted as having a lower degree of emotional and/or sexual involvement than a primary partner.
A partner in a polyamorous relationship who is noted as having a lower degree of emotional and/or sexual involvement than a primary partner but a higher degree than that of a tertiary partner.
A partner in a polyamorous relationship who is noted as having a lower degree of emotional and/or sexual involvement than a secondary partner.
Marital infidelity which occurs under certain (usually threatened) circumstances. For example, if someone threatens to murder their partner unless infidelity occurs.
Recurrent genital pain occurring during, before, or after sexual intercourse.
Pain experienced after coitus.
Pain experienced during coitus.
Pain experienced before coitus.
Pain related to the process of sexual penetration (usually of the vagina).
Pain related to the process of orgasm.
Psychogenic pain related to coitus.
Physiological pain related to coitus.
Fear of, dislike of or prejudice against nonbinary people.
Fear, dislike, or hatred of gender-nonconforming individuals or behavior.
Vaginismus in which someone has never been able to have penetrative intercourse.
Vaginismus in which someone had previously been able to have penetrative intercourse.
Vaginismus that occurs with the onset of menopause.
Vaginismus that occurs near the onset of menopause.
Becoming physiologically capable of sexual reproduction as marked by genital maturation and development of secondary sex characteristics.
The development of one's sexuality, including sexual preferences and sexual orientation.
Consecutive parts of psychosexual development.
Consecutive parts of psychosexual development according to Sigmund Freud.
A central element of the psychoanalytic sexual drive theory, that human beings, from birth, possess an instinctual libido (sexual energy) that develops in five stages.
The stages of development of the psychological aspects of sexuality from birth to adulthood.
Scientific theories falling under the scope of the field of psychology.
Conceptual system developed by Freud and his followers in which unconscious motivations are considered to shape normal and abnormal personality development and behavior.
Sexual behavior that has a significantly high chance of resulting in the transmission of sexual infections, unplanned pregnancy, or other negative consequences.

Note that this phrase (and others similar to it) are discriminatory when applied to LGBTQ+ persons based on their status as LGBTQ+ alone. Being gay, bisexual, lesbian, transgender, queer, or pansexual does not necessarily constitute high-risk sexual behavior.
Behavior considered of an normal sexual nature and therefore likely not clinically significant.
Consecutive parts of psychosexual development which occur abnormally.
Consecutive parts of psychosexual development which occur normally.
Normative sex play due to curiosity observed between siblings.
Normative sex play due to curiosity observed in adolescence.
Normative sex play due to curiosity observed in a group of persons.
Normative sex play due to curiosity observed between companions.
A new pattern of perceptual or ideational material derived from past experience.
A series of thoughts, images, or emotions occurring during sleep which are dissociated from the usual stream of consciousness of the waking state.
An imagined sequence of events or mental images, e.g., daydreams.

A mental image or pattern of thought that stirs a person's sexuality and can create or enhance sexual arousal. A sexual fantasy can be created by the person's imagination or memory, and may be triggered autonomously or by external stimulation such as erotic literature or pornography, a physical object, or sexual attraction to another person.
A sexual fantasy involving imagining or pretending being coerced or coercing another into sexual activity.
